   â”œâ”€â”€ main.tf
   â”œâ”€â”€ variables.tf
   â”œâ”€â”€ terraform.tfstate   ğŸ‘ˆ state file for default workspace
   â””â”€â”€ terraform.tfstate.backup
ğŸ‘‰ All resources (dev, qa, prod, etc.) would share this one state file if you donâ€™t separate them, which can cause conflicts.

ğŸ“‚ Case 2: When you use multiple workspaces
Terraform creates a folder .terraform/terraform.tfstate.d/

Inside it, each workspace gets its own folder with its own state file.

Example:

my-terraform-project/
   â”œâ”€â”€ main.tf
   â”œâ”€â”€ variables.tf
   â”œâ”€â”€ .terraform/
   â”‚     â””â”€â”€ terraform.tfstate.d/
   â”‚           â”œâ”€â”€ dev/
   â”‚           â”‚    â””â”€â”€ terraform.tfstate
   â”‚           â”œâ”€â”€ qa/
   â”‚           â”‚    â””â”€â”€ terraform.tfstate
   â”‚           â””â”€â”€ prod/
   â”‚                â””â”€â”€ terraform.tfstate
ğŸ‘‰ This way, each environment (workspace) is isolated.

ğŸ”‘ Key Point
Default workspace â†’ terraform.tfstate in current folder.

Custom workspaces â†’ terraform.tfstate.d/<workspace-name>/terraform.tfstate inside .terraform.

âš¡ Real-world risk:
If you only use default workspace, and try to deploy dev, qa, and prod from the same code â†’ they will overwrite each other in the same terraform.tfstate. Thatâ€™s why workspaces (or separate folders/repos) are used for environments.

